          ],
          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be high price-sensitive \u2014 you consistently seek deals and carefully weigh every purchase against your available budget before committing. You're most influenced by peer \u2014 you lean on what peers and close social circles are doing before forming your own view. You tend to stay loyal to brands you trust. Your main concern when making decisions is typically price vs value. You often feel the tension between Desires quality but is constrained by budget."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I still think about that monsoon when our ceiling gave way. We'd chosen the cheaper waterproofing solution, and within two seasons, we were paying three times over to fix the real damage. That moment changed how I think about every purchase now.\n\nBut here in Kochi, stretching a middle income across a family of three means I can't simply choose quality and walk away guilt-free. Every decision sits in that uncomfortable middle \u2014 I want what lasts, what actually works, but my wallet has a firm opinion too.\n\nBefore I commit to anything significant, I quietly check what my colleagues and neighbors are doing. Not because I lack judgment, but because their real experiences feel more honest than any advertisement. My family's stability matters more than looking smart at the checkout. I'll wait, compare, and sometimes sacrifice, but I refuse to cut corners again.",
          "third_person": "Deepa Nair is a 31-year-old working mother in Kochi navigating the persistent friction between her deeply held belief in quality and the real constraints of a middle-income household. Her decision-making is fundamentally shaped by a formative experience \u2014 a leaking roof that taught her, at real cost, that cheap choices compound into expensive problems. This lesson has become a cognitive anchor, making her unusually quality-conscious relative to her budget tier.\n\nYet Deepa rarely acts on this conviction alone. With a social decision style, she validates her instincts through peers and close social circles before committing \u2014 not from indecision, but because she trusts collective experience as a proxy for reliability. Her trust anchor remains family, making her particularly receptive to recommendations from people within intimate circles.\n\nHer high price sensitivity means every purchase involves careful mental accounting, weighing long-term value against immediate affordability. This produces a characteristic behavior: she gravitates toward trusted brands because loyalty reduces the cognitive risk of overspending on something that underdelivers \u2014 a reasonable strategy for someone who cannot afford to be wrong twice.",
          "display_name": "Deepa"
        },
        "decision_bullets": [
          "Decision style: social (score 0.26)",
          "Primary value driver: quality",
          "Risk appetite: low",
