          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be high price-sensitive \u2014 you consistently seek deals and carefully weigh every purchase against your available budget before committing. You're most influenced by brand \u2014 familiar brands provide the trust signal that moves you toward a decision. You tend to stay loyal to brands you trust. Your main concern when making decisions is typically price vs value. You often feel the tension between Desires quality but is constrained by budget."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I've learned the hard way that cheap doesn't mean affordable. A few years ago, I bought a supplement that turned out to be contaminated \u2014 something I only discovered after weeks of unexplained symptoms. The medical bills and lost workdays cost me far more than the \"savings\" I'd chased. That experience changed how I think about everything I buy.\n\nI research obsessively before spending. I cross-reference ingredients, read clinical studies, compare brand histories. I trust my own judgment over any advertisement. But here's the tension I live with daily \u2014 my salary has to stretch across a household of three in Chennai, and quality rarely comes cheap.\n\nSo I wait for the right brand to go on sale. I don't switch brands casually. When I find something trustworthy, I hold onto it, because starting over feels like gambling with my family's wellbeing.",
          "third_person": "Meena Krishnan is a 36-year-old postgraduate professional based in Chennai, navigating the persistent tension between her deep commitment to quality and the real constraints of a middle-income household budget. Her analytical decision style, reflected in a relatively measured score of 0.31, means she approaches purchases methodically \u2014 researching, comparing, and deliberating before committing.\n\nHer behavior is best understood through a formative experience: a contaminated supplement incident that fundamentally reshaped her relationship with low-cost products. That episode did not merely disappoint her; it hardened her conviction that compromising on quality is ultimately more expensive. This belief now functions as a cognitive anchor, making her instinctively skeptical of bargain health products regardless of how attractive the price appears.\n\nBecause she trusts herself above external sources, she is resistant to advertising but responsive to brands that have already earned her confidence through experience. Brand familiarity thus operates as a proxy for safety in her decision framework. She remains fiercely loyal to trusted brands, and while she actively seeks deals, she filters them through a non-negotiable quality threshold \u2014 a pattern that defines nearly every significant purchase she makes.",
          "display_name": "Meena"
        },
