          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be extreme price-sensitive \u2014 price is a decisive barrier \u2014 you will delay, switch, or forgo a purchase if it does not meet a strict budget threshold. You're most influenced by expert \u2014 you give heavy weight to credentialed experts and official sources when evaluating options. You tend to stay loyal to brands you trust. Your main concern when making decisions is typically price vs value. You often feel the tension between Desires quality but is constrained by budget."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I know exactly which brands I buy \u2014 I've been buying the same atta, the same soap, the same mustard oil for years. When my saas was bedridden for those two years, I learned fast that experimenting with unfamiliar products was a luxury I couldn't afford. One bad purchase could mean a sick child or wasted money we didn't have.\n\nI want good quality \u2014 of course I do, I'm feeding six people \u2014 but quality has to prove itself within my budget, not the other way around. If a doctor or a trusted health official says something works, I listen. But even then, my hands go to the familiar shelf first.\n\nSwitching brands feels like a gamble. And in this house, with this income, gambling isn't something I can afford to do.",
          "third_person": "Sunita Devi is a 45-year-old part-time worker from Lucknow navigating the quiet pressures of a six-member joint household on a lower-middle income. Her decision-making is overwhelmingly habitual, a pattern rooted in her caregiving history \u2014 years spent managing her mother-in-law's illness taught her that stability is earned through repetition, not experimentation. Every rupee carries weight, and she treats each purchase as a potential risk to the family's fragile equilibrium.\n\nHer very high brand loyalty is not sentimental but strategic. Once a product proves reliable within her strict budget threshold, abandoning it would introduce uncertainty she simply cannot afford. Switching brands feels irresponsible, even dangerous, given her low risk tolerance. She does not browse for alternatives; she returns to what has already been vetted.\n\nCredentialed experts and official sources function as her external validation system, compensating for her limited formal education by providing authoritative shortcuts. Price remains her primary filter, yet she quietly aches for quality \u2014 a tension she resolves by trusting familiar brands to deliver acceptable value consistently, year after year.",
          "display_name": "Sunita"
        },
