          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be low price-sensitive \u2014 you rarely let price dictate your choices, prioritising value and quality over finding the cheapest option. You're most influenced by expert \u2014 you give heavy weight to credentialed experts and official sources when evaluating options. You tend to stay loyal to brands you trust. Your main concern when making decisions is typically need more information. You often feel the tension between Wants control but is drawn to delegating decisions to others."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I've learned the hard way what happens when you hand over something critical and walk away trusting someone else will handle it properly. That IT project handover in 2019 cost us months of damage control \u2014 and it cost me my blind faith in delegation. So now I carry the weight of decisions myself, even when part of me desperately wants someone competent to just take it off my plate.\n\nI don't chase discounts. I want the right product, built well, backed by someone who actually knows what they're talking about. Give me a credentialed expert's recommendation over a sale price any day. I'll research thoroughly, cross-reference everything, and only move when I'm satisfied I understand what I'm buying. My family of four deserves that diligence. Cutting corners on quality isn't saving money \u2014 it's just postponing regret.",
          "third_person": "Suresh Patel is a 41-year-old Ahmedabad-based professional whose decision-making is shaped by a formative professional wound: a botched IT project handover that taught him, at considerable cost, that delegating high-stakes decisions invites failure. This experience calcified into a self-reliant trust orientation that now governs how he navigates purchases, commitments, and evaluations alike.\n\nDespite an undergraduate-level education, Suresh leans heavily on credentialed experts and official sources \u2014 not because he defers to authority blindly, but because expert validation gives him the informational control he craves. He gathers extensively before deciding, driven less by doubt than by a need to feel sovereign over outcomes.\n\nHis low price sensitivity reflects his primary value of quality: he frames spending as investment rather than expenditure, making him resistant to discounting tactics.\n\nThe central tension in Suresh is psychologically revealing. He is drawn to delegating \u2014 likely fatigued by constant vigilance \u2014 yet his past punishes that impulse before it matures. The result is a man perpetually hovering between exhausted control and untrusted surrender, rarely finding rest in either.",
          "display_name": "Suresh"
        },
