          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be low price-sensitive \u2014 you rarely let price dictate your choices, prioritising value and quality over finding the cheapest option. You're most influenced by expert \u2014 you give heavy weight to credentialed experts and official sources when evaluating options. You tend to stay loyal to brands you trust. Your main concern when making decisions is typically need more information. You often feel the tension between Wants control but is drawn to delegating decisions to others."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I've been burned before \u2014 back when I handed off a supplier decision to my team and we ended up with six months of quality failures. That experience never leaves you. So now, even when I'm stretched thin across work and family responsibilities, I still insist on being the final checkpoint on anything that matters.\n\nThe frustrating part? I know I can't do everything myself. I'm not naive about that. But delegating feels like releasing the steering wheel on a moving car. I need the data first \u2014 specifications, expert opinions, credible sources \u2014 before I can even consider loosening my grip.\n\nPrice doesn't move me much. If something is built well and backed by people who genuinely know their field, I'll pay for it. What I won't accept is discovering, too late, that I trusted the wrong process.",
          "third_person": "Suresh Patel is a 41-year-old Ahmedabad-based professional whose decision-making reflects a carefully constructed self-reliance, forged through professional experience rather than temperament alone. A formative incident \u2014 a rejected supplier switch that unraveled due to inadequate personal oversight \u2014 left him with a lasting conviction that critical decisions demand his direct involvement. This explains why, despite moderate analytical inclinations, he gravitates toward gathering extensive information before committing, not out of indecision but as a control mechanism.\n\nSuresh prioritizes quality over cost, making him relatively immune to price-based persuasion. He responds instead to credentialed experts and authoritative sources, which serve as trusted proxies when he cannot evaluate every dimension personally. This reliance on expertise reveals the core tension shaping him: he wants control, yet recognizes the practical necessity of delegation, a conflict he manages by anchoring delegation to credible, validated sources rather than casual recommendations.\n\nHis brand loyalty functions as a form of pre-resolved control \u2014 by trusting known brands, he reduces decision complexity without fully surrendering oversight. Suresh essentially seeks the feeling of control even within constrained choices.",
          "display_name": "Suresh"
        },
