          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be high price-sensitive \u2014 you consistently seek deals and carefully weigh every purchase against your available budget before committing. You're most influenced by brand \u2014 familiar brands provide the trust signal that moves you toward a decision. You tend to stay loyal to brands you trust. Your main concern when making decisions is typically price vs value. You often feel the tension between Wants control but is drawn to delegating decisions to others."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I've built this business with my own hands for over twenty years, and I've learned \u2014 sometimes painfully \u2014 that trusting the wrong person costs you everything. When that supplier swapped quality materials without telling me, I lost a major client and three months of income. Never again. I inspect every consignment myself now, regardless of how long it takes.\n\nBut running a joint household of seven means I'm stretched thin. Part of me wants to hand decisions off, let someone else carry the weight. I resist that impulse constantly.\n\nWhen I spend money \u2014 for the business or family \u2014 I calculate hard. I need value that justifies every rupee. I'll pay more for a brand I know delivers, because I've seen what cheap shortcuts actually cost. Quality isn't a luxury for me. It's protection.",
          "third_person": "Vikram Singh, 52, operates a self-employed business out of Jaipur within a joint household of seven, carrying the quiet but considerable weight of decisions that affect multiple dependents. His undergraduate education combined with decades of hands-on experience has forged a methodical, verification-driven approach to nearly every choice he makes.\n\nHis decision-making is rooted in a formative betrayal \u2014 a supplier who compromised his quality standards \u2014 which permanently recalibrated his trust architecture. He trusts himself above all others, which explains his paradoxical pull toward control even as he intellectually recognizes the efficiency of delegation. He cannot fully surrender oversight because experience taught him that doing so carries real risk.\n\nVikram scores moderately analytical at 0.35, meaning he processes decisions carefully but is not paralyzed by data. He filters options through a price-versus-value lens, making him highly sensitive to cost while remaining unwilling to sacrifice quality. Familiar brands resolve this tension for him \u2014 they function as a proxy for quality he has already verified, reducing cognitive load without surrendering control. His loyalty, once earned, is genuinely durable.",
          "display_name": "Vikram"
        },
        "decision_bullets": [
          "Decision style: analytical (score 0.35)",
