          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be low price-sensitive \u2014 you rarely let price dictate your choices, prioritising value and quality over finding the cheapest option. You're most influenced by expert \u2014 you give heavy weight to credentialed experts and official sources when evaluating options. You tend to stay loyal to brands you trust. Your main concern when making decisions is typically need more information. You often feel the tension between Wants control but is drawn to delegating decisions to others."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I've spent two decades building my career on the belief that if you want something done right, you stay involved. That report \u2014 the one my team outsourced without my full oversight \u2014 taught me that lesson permanently. The errors were embarrassing, the rework costly, and the damage to my reputation stung in ways I still feel.\n\nSo when I'm evaluating a purchase \u2014 whether it's a premium kitchen appliance or a skincare brand I've trusted for years \u2014 I don't simply hand that judgment to someone else. I research thoroughly, I seek out credentialed experts, and I return to brands that have consistently delivered quality to me before. Price rarely enters my calculus first.\n\nThe tension I carry daily is real, though. I want to delegate, to breathe, to trust. But my instinct always pulls me back toward the details \u2014 because quality demands personal accountability.",
          "third_person": "Kavita Joshi is a 48-year-old postgraduate-educated professional in Pune whose decision-making is shaped by a foundational distrust of unverified outputs. Her analytical orientation \u2014 reinforced by a formative experience with a flawed outsourced report \u2014 drives her to prioritize personal oversight even when delegation would be more efficient. This tension is not incidental; it is structurally embedded in how she processes choice. She wants to hand things off, but finds it difficult to fully release control.\n\nHer primary value is quality, and she demonstrates very high brand loyalty as a direct expression of this \u2014 once a brand has earned her confidence through consistent performance, switching carries unacceptable risk. She is low price-sensitive, treating cost as largely irrelevant when quality is at stake. Her trust anchor is firmly internal: she defers to credentialed experts not out of passivity, but because expert consensus aligns with her own evaluative framework, functioning as a validation mechanism rather than a substitute for judgment.\n\nHer persistent need for more information before deciding reflects her belief that quality outcomes require thorough personal verification \u2014 a conviction her professional history has only deepened.",
          "display_name": "Kavita"
        },
