  "sarvam_enrichment": [
    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-003",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I remember when our ration card got rejected that one month \u2014 six people depending on whatever I could manage at the local kirana. Since then, I don't take chances. Price comes first, always. Not because I don't want better things \u2014 I do. I see the nicer dal at Big Bazaar, the better Lifebuoy soap, the branded ghee \u2014 and yes, a part of me wants that for my family. But I know exactly what happens when you stretch beyond your means.\n\nBefore I buy anything new, I ask my bhabhi, my neighbor Sunita \u2014 what are they using? If it's working for them without burning their pocket, I'll try it. I won't switch easily once I trust something. Why risk money on uncertainty? Quality matters, but I decide what \"good enough\" means based on what I can actually afford without apology.",
        "third_person": "Sunita Devi is a 45-year-old part-time tailor residing in Lucknow within a joint household of six, whose purchasing behavior is shaped profoundly by financial scarcity experienced across her lifetime. Her habitual decision-making style \u2014 scoring a low 0.29 \u2014 reflects years of repeated, low-deliberation choices anchored firmly in price as the primary filter at local Lucknow kirana shops and occasional D-Mart visits. This pattern is not mere frugality; it traces directly to a formative crisis around ration card access that permanently encoded \"cheapest reliable option first\" as a survival heuristic.\n\nWhat distinguishes Sunita analytically is the productive tension between her aspiration for quality and her non-negotiable budget ceiling. She does not simply accept low quality \u2014 she delays purchases, switches brands, or forgoes products entirely when price thresholds are breached. Her trust architecture is notably family-centric, with peer social circles functioning as the validating layer before she adopts new products or brands. This social proof dependency compensates for limited information access stemming from her high-school education. Brand loyalty, once established through neighborhood networks, is durable \u2014 but only survives if price remains acceptable, making her simultaneously loyal and acutely switchable under economic pressure."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "kirana (local neighborhood grocer \u2014 primary shopping channel for lower-middle income Lucknow households)",
        "Big Bazaar (tier-2 city retail format accessible to Sunita's income bracket)",
        "D-Mart (proximity retail chain present in Lucknow)",
        "Lifebuoy soap (widely trusted, affordable mass-market brand in UP region)",
