    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-005",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I still think about our wedding budget crisis \u2014 how we stretched every rupee but refused to cut corners on the things that actually mattered. That experience taught me something I carry into every purchase now: quality in the right places is everything.\n\nLiving in Kochi on a middle income, with a young family depending on me, I can't afford mistakes. I research carefully before buying anything significant \u2014 I check what my friends and colleagues are using, what their honest experiences have been. Their opinions matter more to me than any advertisement.\n\nThe real struggle is internal \u2014 I see something well-made and I want it, but my mind immediately calculates whether it truly fits our budget. I'm not chasing cheap. I'm chasing value that won't disappoint me six months later, whether it's from a trusted brand at Lulu or a local Kerala spice merchant. That line is where I live every single day.",
        "third_person": "Deepa Nair is a 31-year-old working woman based in Kochi, navigating the demands of early family life within a nuclear household of three on a middle income. Her purchasing behavior is shaped by a formative experience \u2014 a wedding budget crisis that fundamentally restructured how she thinks about value. Rather than spreading resources thinly, she learned to concentrate quality where it matters most, making her selectively demanding rather than uniformly frugal.\n\nHer analytical decision style manifests as careful deliberation before any significant purchase \u2014 comparing prices at Lulu Hypermarket or local neighbourhood supermarkets, weighing Malayalam-language peer reviews, and consulting her mother in Thrissur before committing. This tension \u2014 wanting quality but facing real budget constraints \u2014 keeps her perpetually evaluating trade-offs. Once a brand earns her confidence, she stays loyal, viewing switching as an unnecessary risk to her household's wellbeing."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "Lulu Hypermarket (Kochi retail anchor, tier-2 city middle-income shopping)",
        "local Kerala spice merchant (regional food sourcing authenticity)",
        "mother in Thrissur (pre-existing family geography, reinforces family-over-institutions pattern)",
        "Malayalam-language peer reviews (regional linguistic specificity, peer-influence behavior)"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
        {
          "original": "advertisement",
          "replacement": "advertisement (kept generic \u2014 peer validation is the core attribute, not specific media channel)",
          "attribute_source": "behavioral_summary.peer_influence"
        },
        {
          "original": "what my friends and colleagues are using",
          "replacement": "what my friends and colleagues are using (kept as-is \u2014 peer circle validation already reflects Kochi professional context)",
          "attribute_source": "location.city, employment.full_time"
        }
      ],
      "validation_status": {
        "cr1_isolation": "pass",
