    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-017",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I still think about that monsoon when our ceiling gave way. We'd chosen the cheaper waterproofing contractor, and within two seasons, we were paying three times over to fix the real damage. That moment changed how I think about every purchase now.\n\nBut here in Kochi, stretching a middle income across a family of three means I can't simply choose quality and walk away guilt-free. Every decision sits in that uncomfortable middle \u2014 I want what lasts, what actually works, but my wallet has a firm opinion too.\n\nBefore I commit to anything significant, I quietly check what my colleagues at the office and neighbors around Fort Kochi are doing. Not because I lack judgment, but because their real experiences feel more honest than any advertisement. My family's stability matters more than looking smart at the checkout. I'll wait, compare, and sometimes sacrifice, but I refuse to cut corners again \u2014 not after what happened with Arjun's rash from that budget baby brand.",
        "third_person": "Deepa Nair is a 31-year-old working mother in Kochi navigating the persistent friction between her deeply held belief in quality and the real constraints of a middle-income household. Her decision-making is fundamentally shaped by a formative experience \u2014 a leaking roof during monsoon season that taught her, at real cost, that cheap contractors compound into expensive problems. This lesson has become a cognitive anchor, making her unusually quality-conscious relative to her budget tier.\n\nYet Deepa rarely acts on this conviction alone. With a peer-influenced decision style, she validates her instincts through colleagues and neighbors in Kochi's middle-class residential circles before committing \u2014 not from indecision, but because she trusts collective experience as a proxy for reliability. Her trust anchor remains family, making her particularly receptive to recommendations from her mother and husband. Her high price sensitivity means every purchase involves careful mental accounting, weighing long-term value against immediate affordability. This produces characteristic behavior: she gravitates toward trusted brands\u2014often mid-range Kerala staples\u2014because loyalty reduces the cognitive risk of overspending on something that underdelivers."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "Fort Kochi (neighborhood specificity)",
        "monsoon season (regional seasonal context)",
        "Kerala staples (regional brand preference)",
        "budget baby brand (product category traceable to life story age 30)",
        "colleagues at the office (peer validation in urban Kochi context)"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
        {
          "original": "a cheaper contractor",
          "replacement": "the cheaper waterproofing contractor",
          "attribute_source": "life_story.age_28"
        },
        {
          "original": "colleagues and neighbors",
          "replacement": "colleagues at the office and neighbors around Fort Kochi",
          "attribute_source": "location.city"
        },
        {
