    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-009",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I've learned the hard way that cheap doesn't mean affordable. A few years ago, I bought a supplement from an unverified seller that turned out to be contaminated \u2014 something I only discovered after weeks of unexplained symptoms. The Apollo Hospital bills and lost workdays cost me far more than the 'savings' I'd chased. That experience changed how I think about everything I buy.\n\nI research obsessively before spending. I cross-reference ingredients, read clinical studies, compare brand histories on trusted platforms like 1mg. I trust my own judgment over any advertisement. But here's the tension I live with daily \u2014 my salary has to stretch across a household of three in Chennai, and quality rarely comes cheap.\n\nSo I wait for the right brand to go on sale at Nykaa or BigBasket. I don't switch brands casually. When I find something trustworthy, I hold onto it, because starting over feels like gambling with my family's wellbeing.",
        "third_person": "Meena Krishnan is a 36-year-old postgraduate professional based in Chennai, navigating the persistent tension between her deep commitment to quality and the real constraints of a middle-income household budget. Her analytical decision style means she approaches purchases methodically \u2014 researching, comparing, and deliberating before committing, often cross-referencing reviews on 1mg or BigBasket.\n\nHer behavior is best understood through a formative experience: a contaminated supplement incident that landed her in Apollo Hospital, fundamentally reshaaping her relationship with low-cost products. That episode did not merely disappoint her; it hardened her conviction that compromising on quality is ultimately more expensive. This belief now functions as a cognitive anchor, making her instinctively skeptical of bargain health products regardless of how attractive the price appears.\n\nBecause she trusts herself above external sources, she is resistant to advertising but responsive to established Indian brands that have earned her confidence through experience. Brand familiarity operates as a proxy for safety in her decision framework. She remains fiercely loyal to trusted brands, and while she actively seeks deals through verified platforms, she filters them through a non-negotiable quality threshold."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "Apollo Hospital (Chennai-specific healthcare institution, middle-income accessible)",
        "1mg (trusted online health/wellness platform for middle-income Indian consumers)",
        "BigBasket (Chennai-accessible e-commerce for grocery/health products)",
        "Nykaa (premium beauty/wellness brand trusted by middle-income professionals)"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
        {
          "original": "The medical bills and lost workdays cost me far more",
          "replacement": "The Apollo Hospital bills and lost workdays cost me far more",
          "attribute_source": "location.city, income_bracket"
        },
        {
          "original": "I cross-reference ingredients, read clinical studies",
          "replacement": "I cross-reference ingredients on trusted platforms like 1mg, read clinical studies",
          "attribute_source": "education.postgraduate, location.metro, behavior.research_intensive"
        },
        {
          "original": "So I wait for the right brand to go on sale",
          "replacement": "So I wait for the right brand to go on sale at Nykaa or BigBasket",
          "attribute_source": "location.city, income_bracket, household.size"
        }
      ],
      "validation_status": {
        "cr1_isolation": "pass",
        "cr2_stereotype_audit": "not_run",
        "cr3_cultural_realism": "not_run",
