    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-015",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I know exactly which brands I buy \u2014 I've been buying the same Aashirvaad atta, the same Lifebuoy soap, the same Gemini mustard oil for years from the local kirana for nearly two decades. When my saas was bedridden for those two years, I learned fast that experimenting with unfamiliar products was a luxury I couldn't afford. One bad purchase could mean a sick child or wasted money we didn't have.\n\nI want good quality \u2014 of course I do, I'm feeding six people \u2014 but quality has to prove itself within my budget, not the other way around. If a doctor at the government clinic or a trusted health official says something works, I listen. But even then, my hands go to the familiar shelf first.\n\nSwitching brands feels like a gamble. And in this house, with this income, gambling isn't something I can afford to do.",
        "third_person": "Sunita Devi is a 45-year-old part-time garment-shop worker from Lucknow navigating the quiet pressures of a six-member joint household on a lower-middle income. Her decision-making is overwhelmingly habitual, a pattern rooted in her caregiving history \u2014 years spent managing her mother-in-law's kidney illness taught her that stability is earned through repetition, not experimentation. Every rupee carries weight, and she treats each purchase as a potential risk to the family's fragile equilibrium.\n\nHer very high brand loyalty is not sentimental but strategic. Once a product like Aashirvaad atta or Lifebuoy proves reliable within her strict budget threshold at the neighbourhood kirana, abandoning it would introduce uncertainty she simply cannot afford. Credentialed experts \u2014 government doctors, health officials \u2014 function as her external validation system, compensating for her high-school education by providing authoritative shortcuts. Price remains her primary filter, yet she quietly aches for quality \u2014 a tension she resolves by trusting familiar brands to deliver acceptable value consistently, year after year."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "Aashirvaad atta (market-leading wheat flour brand, appropriate for lower-middle income household)",
        "Lifebuoy soap (accessible, trusted mass-market brand consistent with income and region)",
        "Gemini mustard oil (regional North Indian oil brand, common in Lucknow households)",
        "local kirana (authentic retail touchpoint for lower-middle income Lucknow shoppers)",
        "government clinic (credible expert source for lower-middle income household in tier-2 city)"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
