    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-008",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I've learned the hard way what happens when you hand over something critical and walk away trusting someone else will handle it properly. That ERP migration in 2019 cost us months of damage control \u2014 and it cost me my blind faith in delegation. So now I carry the weight of decisions myself, even when part of me desperately wants someone competent to just take it off my plate.\n\nI don't chase discounts. I want the right product, built well, backed by someone who actually knows what they're talking about. Give me a credentialed expert's recommendation over a sale price any day. I'll research thoroughly on industry portals, cross-reference everything, and only move when I'm satisfied I understand what I'm buying. My family of four deserves that diligence. Cutting corners on quality isn't saving money \u2014 it's just postponing regret.",
        "third_person": "Suresh Patel is a 41-year-old Ahmedabad-based professional whose decision-making is shaped by a formative professional wound: a botched ERP module handover that taught him, at considerable cost, that delegating high-stakes technical decisions invites failure. This experience, witnessed firsthand during those grueling 14-hour salvage nights, calcified into a self-reliant trust orientation that now governs how he navigates purchases, commitments, and evaluations alike.\n\nDespite undergraduate credentials, Suresh leans heavily on certified professionals and structured expert sources\u2014not because he defers blindly, but because credentialed validation gives him the informational control he craves. He gathers extensively through official channels before deciding, driven less by doubt than by a need to feel sovereign over outcomes.\n\nHis low price sensitivity reflects his primary value of quality: he frames spending as investment rather than expenditure, making him resistant to discounting tactics. His fixed-rate Bopal property deal exemplifies this\u2014three years of methodical saving over leveraged speed.\n\nThe central tension in Suresh is psychologically revealing. He is drawn to delegating\u2014likely fatigued by constant vigilance\u2014yet his past punishes that impulse before it matures. The result is a man perpetually hovering between exhausted control and untrusted surrender, rarely finding rest in either."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "ERP migration (specific to Ahmedabad tech sector)",
        "industry portals (credentialed expert sources culturally authentic to Indian professional context)",
        "Bopal property deal (specific Ahmedabad locality, upper-middle class housing market)",
        "fixed-rate financial strategy (Indian mortgage context)"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
        {
          "original": "IT project handover",
          "replacement": "ERP migration",
          "attribute_source": "life_story.age_29 + location.city"
        },
        {
          "original": "sale price",
          "replacement": "discounting tactics",
          "attribute_source": "behavioral_summary.price_sensitivity + location.metro_context"
        },
        {
          "original": "research thoroughly",
          "replacement": "research thoroughly on industry portals",
          "attribute_source": "behavioral_summary.expert_influence + location.city"
        }
      ],
      "validation_status": {
        "cr1_isolation": "pass",
        "cr2_stereotype_audit": "not_run",
        "cr3_cultural_realism": "not_run",
        "cr4_persona_fidelity": "not_run"
      },
      "skip_reason": null
