    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-020",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I've been burned before \u2014 back when I handed off a supplier decision to my team and we ended up with six months of quality failures. That experience never leaves you. So now, even when I'm stretched thin across work and family responsibilities, I still insist on being the final checkpoint on anything that matters.\n\nThe frustrating part? I know I can't do everything myself. I'm not naive about that. But delegating feels like releasing the steering wheel on a moving car. I need the data first \u2014 ISO certifications, expert assessments from credible auditors, third-party test reports \u2014 before I can even consider loosening my grip.\n\nPrice doesn't move me much. If something is built well and backed by people who genuinely know their field, I'll pay for it. What I won't accept is discovering, too late, that I trusted the wrong process.",
        "third_person": "Suresh Patel is a 41-year-old Ahmedabad-based professional whose decision-making reflects a carefully constructed self-reliance, forged through procurement-sector experience rather than temperament alone. A formative incident \u2014 a rejected supplier switch that unraveled due to inadequate personal oversight \u2014 left him with a lasting conviction that critical decisions demand his direct involvement. This explains why, despite moderate analytical inclinations, he gravitates toward gathering extensive documentation before committing, not out of indecision but as a control mechanism.\n\nSuresh prioritizes quality over cost, making him relatively immune to price-based persuasion. He responds instead to credentialed auditors and authoritative certifications \u2014 ISO standards, third-party test labs, industry-recognized assessments \u2014 which serve as trusted proxies when he cannot evaluate every dimension personally. This reliance on formal expertise reveals the core tension shaping him: he wants control, yet recognizes the practical necessity of delegation, a conflict he manages by anchoring delegation to verifiable, validated sources rather than casual recommendations. His brand loyalty functions as pre-resolved control."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "ISO certifications (professional verification standard used across Indian manufacturing and procurement)",
        "third-party test reports (formal auditing practice in Indian corporate environments)",
        "Ahmedabad-based procurement sector context (Gujarat's manufacturing and textile supply chain ecosystem)"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
        {
          "original": "expert opinions, credible sources",
          "replacement": "ISO certifications, expert assessments from credible auditors, third-party test reports",
          "attribute_source": "employment: full-time procurement analyst, location.region: Gujarat manufacturing hub"
        },
        {
          "original": "generic 'data' reference",
          "replacement": "ISO standards, third-party test labs, industry-recognized assessments",
          "attribute_source": "life_story age 35: quality audit and 22-page report pattern, income: upper-middle professional"
        }
      ],
      "validation_status": {
        "cr1_isolation": "pass",
        "cr2_stereotype_audit": "not_run",
        "cr3_cultural_realism": "not_run",
        "cr4_persona_fidelity": "not_run"
      },
      "skip_reason": null
    },
    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-018",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I've built this business with my own hands for over twenty years, and I've learned \u2014 sometimes painfully \u2014 that trusting the wrong person costs you everything. When that supplier in Sindhi Camp swapped quality materials without telling me, I lost a major client and three months of income. Never again. I inspect every consignment myself now, regardless of how long it takes.\n\nBut running a joint household of seven means I'm stretched thin. Part of me wants to hand decisions off, let someone else carry the weight. I resist that impulse constantly.\n\nWhen I spend money \u2014 for the business or family \u2014 I calculate hard. I need value that justifies every rupee. I'll pay more for a brand I know delivers, because I've seen what cheap shortcuts actually cost. Quality isn't a luxury for me. It's protection.",
        "third_person": "Vikram Singh, 52, operates a self-employed garment trading firm out of Sindhi Camp market in Jaipur within a joint household of seven, carrying the quiet but considerable weight of decisions that affect multiple dependents. His undergraduate education combined with decades of hands-on experience in Jaipur's textile wholesale trade has forged a methodical, verification-driven approach to nearly every choice he makes.\n\nHis decision-making is rooted in a formative betrayal \u2014 a Sindhi Camp supplier who compromised his quality standards \u2014 which permanently recalibrated his trust architecture. He trusts himself above all others, which explains his paradoxical pull toward control even as he intellectually recognizes the efficiency of delegation. He cannot fully surrender oversight because experience taught him that doing so carries real risk.\n\nVikram scores moderately analytical at 0.35, meaning he processes decisions carefully but is not paralyzed by data. He filters options through a price-versus-value lens, making him highly sensitive to cost while remaining unwilling to sacrifice quality. Familiar brands \u2014 those he has vetted through his own Jaipur market networks \u2014 resolve this tension for him, functioning as a proxy for quality already verified. His loyalty, once earned, is genuinely durable."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "Sindhi Camp market (Jaipur textile wholesale hub)",
        "Sindhi Camp supplier (context-specific)",
        "Jaipur's textile wholesale trade",
        "Jaipur market networks"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
        {
          "original": "a supplier",
          "replacement": "a supplier in Sindhi Camp",
          "attribute_source": "location.city + life_story_age_31"
        },
        {
          "original": "out of Jaipur within a joint household",
          "replacement": "out of Sindhi Camp market in Jaipur within a joint household",
          "attribute_source": "location.city + household.structure + life_story_age_38"
        },
        {
          "original": "familiar brands resolve this tension for him",
          "replacement": "familiar brands \u2014 those he has vetted through his own Jaipur market networks \u2014 resolve this tension for him",
          "attribute_source": "location.city + employment.self_employed + behavioral_summary"
        }
      ],
      "validation_status": {
        "cr1_isolation": "pass",
        "cr2_stereotype_audit": "not_run",
        "cr3_cultural_realism": "not_run",
        "cr4_persona_fidelity": "not_run"
      },
      "skip_reason": null
    },
    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-011",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I've spent two decades building my career on the belief that if you want something done right, you stay involved. That report \u2014 the one my team outsourced without my full oversight \u2014 taught me that lesson permanently. The errors were embarrassing, the rework costly, and the damage to my reputation stung in ways I still feel.\n\nSo when I'm evaluating a purchase \u2014 whether it's a premium kitchen appliance from Croma or a skincare brand I've trusted for years \u2014 I don't simply hand that judgment to someone else. I research thoroughly, I seek out credentialed experts, and I return to brands that have consistently delivered quality to me before. Price rarely enters my calculus first.\n\nThe tension I carry daily is real, though. I want to delegate, to breathe, to trust. But my instinct always pulls me back toward the details \u2014 because quality demands personal accountability.",
        "third_person": "Kavita Joshi is a 48-year-old postgraduate-educated professional in Pune whose decision-making is shaped by a foundational distrust of unverified outputs. Her analytical orientation \u2014 reinforced by a formative experience with a flawed outsourced report \u2014 drives her to prioritize personal oversight even when delegation would be more efficient. This tension is not incidental; it is structurally embedded in how she processes choice. She wants to hand things off, but finds it difficult to fully release control.\n\nHer primary value is quality, and she demonstrates very high brand loyalty as a direct expression of this \u2014 once a brand has earned her confidence through consistent performance, switching carries unacceptable risk. She is low price-sensitive, treating cost as largely irrelevant when quality is at stake. Her trust anchor is firmly internal: she defers to credentialed experts \u2014 whether consumer reports from The Times of India or product certifications \u2014 not out of passivity, but because expert consensus aligns with her own evaluative framework, functioning as a validation mechanism rather than a substitute for judgment.\n\nHer persistent need for more information before deciding reflects her belief that quality outcomes require thorough personal verification \u2014 a conviction her professional history and her Symbiosis degree have only deepened."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "Croma (premium electronics retailer, upper-middle income, metro context)",
