    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-014",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I tell myself I've outgrown needing anyone's approval \u2014 and mostly, I believe that. The thesis rejection taught me something uncomfortable: institutional validation is noise. My judgment holds. But then I'll spend forty minutes checking what people in my network think before buying a laptop I've already cross-referenced on Tech2 and Digit before committing. That contradiction sits in my chest without resolution.\n\nLiving alone in Bengaluru, every purchase decision lands entirely on me. I don't mind that weight \u2014 I actually prefer it. What I won't do is compromise on quality. Cheap options feel like a small betrayal of the standards I've built for myself.\n\nI'll research obsessively, cross-reference specs, read deeply \u2014 but I'll still casually mention the decision to two or three people I respect over a coffee at Starbucks or via Slack. Not for permission. Just... confirmation that I'm not missing something obvious. The line between those two things blurs more than I'd like to admit.",
        "third_person": "Rahul Verma is a 28-year-old Bengaluru-based tech professional whose decision-making reveals a compelling internal contradiction: a man who intellectually prizes self-reliance yet remains meaningfully tethered to peer validation. His postgraduate background and formative experience with academic rejection forged a quality-first orientation \u2014 he rarely compromises on standards and shows little sensitivity to price when investing in something worthwhile, whether premium coworking spaces or boutique stays in Coorg.\n\nWhat makes Rahul analytically interesting is the gap between his self-image and his actual behavior. He perceives himself as autonomous and evidence-driven, yet peer signals through his Bengaluru tech circles consistently shape his initial consideration set before he forms independent conclusions. This suggests his independence is largely post-hoc rationalization rather than genuine first-principles thinking.\n\nHis tendency to explore alternatives readily, combined with persistent information-seeking across tech forums and product review ecosystems, reflects an underlying anxiety about making the wrong call without sufficient social proof. Living alone amplifies this \u2014 without ambient household opinion to absorb, he substitutes peer networks more deliberately. Rahul's trust anchor remains nominally the self, but his behavior tells a more socially contingent story."
      },
